## Column Types

### String Types

```ruby
# string - VARCHAR(255) - for short text
t.string :title
t.string :email, limit: 100

# text - TEXT - for long text
t.text :body
t.text :description

# When to use:
# string: titles, names, emails, slugs (< 255 chars)
# text: article bodies, descriptions, comments (> 255 chars)
```

### Numeric Types

```ruby
# integer - INT - whole numbers
t.integer :age
t.integer :views_count, default: 0

# bigint - BIGINT - large whole numbers
t.bigint :user_id

# decimal - DECIMAL - precise numbers (money)
t.decimal :price, precision: 10, scale: 2
# precision: total digits
# scale: digits after decimal
# Example: 12345678.90 (10 digits, 2 after decimal)

# float - FLOAT - approximate numbers
t.float :latitude
t.float :longitude

# When to use:
# integer: counts, ages, quantities
# bigint: large IDs, large counts
# decimal: money, precise calculations
# float: coordinates, scientific data
```

### Boolean

```ruby
# boolean - BOOLEAN
t.boolean :published, default: false
t.boolean :active, default: true
t.boolean :admin, default: false, null: false

# In queries:
Article.where(published: true)
User.where(admin: false)
```

### Date & Time

```ruby
# date - DATE - date only (YYYY-MM-DD)
t.date :birth_date
t.date :published_on

# datetime - DATETIME - date and time
t.datetime :published_at
t.datetime :expires_at

# timestamps - creates created_at and updated_at
t.timestamps

# When to use:
# date: birthdays, deadlines (no time needed)
# datetime: events, logs (need time)
# timestamps: audit trail (always include!)
```

### JSON

```ruby
# json - JSON - structured data
t.json :metadata
t.json :settings
t.json :preferences

# jsonb - JSONB (PostgreSQL only) - binary JSON, faster queries
t.jsonb :data

# Example usage:
Article.create(
  title: "Test",
  metadata: { tags: ["ruby", "rails"], featured: true }
)

Article.where("metadata->>'featured' = ?", "true")
```

### Binary

```ruby
# binary - BLOB - binary data
t.binary :file_data

# Note: Use ActiveStorage for file uploads instead!
```

### Other Types

```ruby
# uuid - UUID - universally unique identifier
t.uuid :uuid

# inet - INET (PostgreSQL) - IP addresses
t.inet :ip_address

# array - ARRAY (PostgreSQL) - array of values
t.string :tags, array: true, default: []

# hstore - HSTORE (PostgreSQL) - key-value pairs
t.hstore :properties
```

